Your Honor,

I stand before you today to plead guilty to the offense of stealing 1000 pounds from the cash register at the café where I used to work. I am deeply remorseful for my actions and fully accept responsibility for the harm I have caused.

I understand that my actions have betrayed the trust that my former boss had placed in me. I apologize sincerely for abusing that trust and recognize the impact it has had on both her and the business. It was a grave mistake on my part, and I regret the consequences it has brought upon myself and others.

I would like to emphasize that this is the first and only offense on my record. I have never been involved in any criminal activity before, and I am committed to ensuring that it remains the only instance. My clean record is a testament to my character and the fact that I have always strived to live a lawful and responsible life.

At the age of 25, I am still young and have much to learn. I realize now the gravity of my actions and the consequences they carry. I assure the court that I have taken this experience as a lesson and am determined to rectify the wrong I have done. I understand the importance of making amends and pledge to eventually repay the amount I stole, even though I currently lack the financial means to do so.

In terms of mitigating factors, I acknowledge that there were no external provocation or circumstances that led me to commit this crime. This offense was solely an act of personal misconduct, for which I take full responsibility. However, just stating that I am pleading guilty itself serves as a mitigating factor, as it demonstrates my recognition of my wrongdoing and my willingness to take accountability for my actions.

While I do not have any mental illness or disability that influenced my behavior, I am aware of the need to actively prevent myself from engaging in such behavior in the future. I have taken steps to reflect on my actions and have enrolled in counseling sessions to explore the underlying factors that led to my misconduct. These sessions have helped me gain a deeper understanding of myself and have equipped me with the necessary tools to make better choices moving forward.

I have already suffered the consequences of my crime, with the loss of my job and the profound impact it has had on my personal and professional life. The shame and regret I carry with me every day serve as a constant reminder of the gravity of my actions. I can assure the court that I am dedicated to using this experience as a turning point in my life, to bring about positive change and become a productive member of society.

Your Honor, I respectfully ask for leniency and understanding in the sentencing process. I am committed to making amends, making changes, and becoming a better person. Your consideration of my genuine remorse, my clean record, my commitment to personal growth, and my desire to eventually compensate for the harm caused would be greatly appreciated.

Thank you for allowing me to address the court.

